</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>a special p=
urpose acquisition company? Here is the story that I would have told you a =
year ago, at the height of the SPAC boom. A SPAC is a pool of money that a =
sponsor raises to take a private company public. The sponsor sells stock in=
 the SPAC at $10 per share=C2=A0(say she sells 20 million shares for $200 m=
illion), puts the money in a pot,=C2=A0and goes out looking for a private c=
ompany. When she finds a promising private company, the sponsor says, look,=
 I=E2=80=99ve got $200 million in my pot,=C2=A0and=C2=A0the pot is a public=
ly listed stock; if you merge with my pot, you will get the money to run yo=
ur business, and you will have a public listing.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">The private company will find this appealing. For one thing, it is a =
faster and easier route to a public listing than a traditional initial publ=
ic offering: Merging with an existing public company (the SPAC) is a bit qu=
icker and more reliable than filing your own prospectus to go public, and y=
ou have a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25172656=
.276397/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQ=
tMTIvbWF5YmUtc3BhY3MtYXJlLXJlYWxseS1pcG9z/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3a00376f=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> bit mor=
e leeway</a> in how you market your stock if you=E2=80=99re doing a merger =
rather than an IPO.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For another thing, it o=
ffers the private company much more <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/25172656.276397/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL=
25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjAtMDYtMjMvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4td2FudHMtYS1t=
YXR1cmUtdW5pY29ybg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBec09a0a6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">certainty of price and size</a>=
: With a SPAC deal, the private company and the sponsor agree on a valuatio=
n, and then the sponsor hands over the pot of money at that valuation. Inst=
ead of launching an IPO and hoping to be able to raise $200 million at a pr=
ice you like, you can agree on the price and the $200 million with the SPAC=
 sponsor in advance; then you announce the deal with the money already ther=
e.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors in the SPAC also find this app=
ealing: It is, in effect, a way to invest in a company as it goes public, a=
longside a smart investor (the SPAC sponsor) at the going-public price. Nor=
mally, IPOs are allocated to big institutional investors; ordinary retail i=
nvestors can=E2=80=99t buy newly public stocks until they start trading on =
the exchange, usually at a much higher price (the =E2=80=9CIPO pop=E2=80=9D=
). With a SPAC, if you put your $10 into the pot, and the SPAC announces a =
good deal, the SPAC will trade up, and you will benefit from <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25172656.276397/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMjMvdGVzbGEtcml2YWwtbHV=
jaWQtbW90b3JzLXBhaWQtYS1wcmljZS1mb3ItaXRzLXNwYWMtZGVhbA/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB48dd0615" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> the SPAC pop</a>.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This story w=
as not wrong, really, and it accurately captured a lot of the dynamics of t=
he SPAC market in late 2020 and early 2021. It elides certain details. I di=
dn=E2=80=99t mention that SPACs offer their investors <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25172656.276397/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDEtMDgvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtc3BhYy1tYW=
dpYy1pc24tdC1mcmVl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc12c7a57" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">withdrawal rights</a>: If you d=
on=E2=80=99t like the deal that a SPAC does, you can get your $10 back, wit=
h a bit of interest. That undermines the price-and-size-certainty argument =
for SPACs, but it didn=E2=80=99t matter all that much because, at the time,=
 SPAC deals were hot, they traded up on announcement, and so no one had muc=
h reason to withdraw their money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I would n=
o longer tell you this story. Now here is how a SPAC (sometimes)=C2=A0works=
:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16p=
x 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A sponsor raises money from inve=
stors at $10 a share. Say she raises $200 million by selling 20 million sha=
res.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The sponsor finds a private c=
ompany to merge with and agrees on a price. Say they value the private comp=
any at $800 million pre-money; the SPAC=E2=80=99s $200 million will buy 20%=
 of the combined company.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The spon=
sor and the private company go out and find PIPE investors (=E2=80=9Cprivat=
e investment in public equity=E2=80=9D), institutional investors (including=
 perhaps=C2=A0the private company=E2=80=99s existing investors, or the SPAC=
 sponsor=E2=80=99s own investment funds) that want to invest in the private=
 company in the SPAC merger. Say they raise $150 million of PIPE money.</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The sponsor and the private company a=
nnounce their merger.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The SPAC inv=
estors take all their money back. They get back, like, $10.01 per share, wi=
th the extra penny being interest that the SPAC earned on their money. Actu=
ally I exaggerate; really only 95% of the SPAC investors take their money b=
ack. There is $10 million left in the SPAC pool.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">The SPAC and the private company merge. The combined company=
 has $160 million of cash, $150 million from the PIPE deal and $10 million =
from what=E2=80=99s left in the SPAC pool.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">The combined company is also public, with a valuation of about $96=
0 million ($800 million pre-money valuation plus $160 million of new cash) =
and a public=C2=A0float of about $10 million.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s =E2=80=A6=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s weird, right? The <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25172656.276397/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMWE5YmUwNGUtYTI5OC00OWJiLWEzZDgtMmVmZWUyMmJj=
YTAx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB94a2867f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">Financial Times reports</a>:</p><blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors are pulling cash out of special purpo=
se acquisition companies at increasingly higher rates, with a number of veh=
icles having their trust accounts almost wiped out as more than 90 per cent=
 of their shareholders redeemed investments.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">The average redemption rate during the third quarter was 52.4 per cent, a=
ccording to data provider Dealogic. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">The trend casts doubt over claims that listing through a Spac offers gre=
ater deal certainty than a traditional initial public offering, one of the =
key benefits touted by proponents.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">I have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
25172656.276397/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMjEtMDQtMTMvZ3JhYi1zcGFjLW1lZ2EtbWVyZ2VyLWlzbi10LW1lZ2Etd2l0aG91dC1ibGFja3=
JvY2stcGlwZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB23a6ce34" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> argued before</a> that in some sense=
 the platonic form of a SPAC is to get rid of the pool of cash. Without the=
 pool of cash, a SPAC deal looks more or less like (1) you raise a final pr=
ivate investment round (from the PIPE investors) and then (2) you do a dire=
ct listing so your stock can trade on the stock exchange. With some SPACs i=
t does seem like a direct listing would have been easier:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Biopharmaceutical start-up eFFECTOR Therapeutics=
 expected to receive at least $100m in proceeds from its merger with Locust=
 Walk Acquisition, a Spac that raised $175m when it listed in January. Howe=
ver, the cash held in the trust account was almost entirely wiped out when =
97 per cent of shareholders chose to redeem, leaving just $5.2m.=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While some of the shortfall was covered by a $6=
0m private investment in public equity transaction, eFFECTOR received just =
$53.5m after fees and expenses.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">It got $5.2 million of public money and $60 million of private mone=
y, though about two-thirds of that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/25172656.276397/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZG=
dhci9kYXRhLzE4Mjg1MjIvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIxMjQxOTk0L2QxNTk2OTVkNDI0YjMuaHRt/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf048f45f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">came from its existing investors</a>. Its capital stru=
cture barely budged; the SPAC did nothing for it as a fundraising tool. But=
 it is public now; that=E2=80=99s something.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">But here=E2=80=99s the really weird thing about these busted SPACs. Why w=
ould investors withdraw 97% of their money from a SPAC? Presumably the answ=
er is that they think the merger deal is worth less than $10 per share. Giv=
en the choice of a share of eFFECTOR Therapeutics stock or $10 in cash, 97%=
 of Locust Walk shareholders chose the $10.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>You might think that, after that, the remaining shares might trade down: T=
he market voted that they were worth less than $10, so presumably they=E2=
=80=99d trade for less than $10. Or maybe they=E2=80=99d trade at $10, beca=
use the people who chose to keep them think they=E2=80=99re worth $10 (and =
declined the cash). Or maybe $10.20, for scarcity value or something.=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fact, in the days leading up to the=
 closing of the merger and the redemption of 97% of Locust Walk=E2=80=99s s=
tock, the shares traded below $10. And then the merger <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25172656.276397/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLm=
dvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMDAwMTgyODUyMi8wMDAxMTkzMTI1MjEyN=
jIwNjAvZDIxNDc3OWQ4ay5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc741967c" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">closed on Aug. 25</a> a=
nd the stock went to $16.98. Weird! By Sept. 3 it was back down to $8.56. B=
y Sept. 13 it was at $26.73. It closed yesterday at $16.89.=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The main point to make here, I think, is that you ha=
ve a company with a market capitalization of more than $600 million, very l=
ittle of which trades. The day after the merger closed, the stock available=
 to trade was basically the $5.2 million worth of SPAC stock that had not r=
edeemed. A tiny float makes for volatile trading.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">This is actually a common SPAC story now. The <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25172656.276397/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNv=
bS9hcnRpY2xlcy9hZnRlci1lYXJseS1pbnZlc3RvcnMtZmxlZS1zcGFjLWRlYWxzLWRheS10cmF=
kZXJzLXJ1c2gtaW4tMTE2MzI2ODQzMjU_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zMw/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB41ba2893" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">Wall Street Journal has a story</a> about all the SPACs that have had=
 heavy redemptions followed by wild price rallies:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Day traders are targeting some companies that recently=
 closed SPAC mergers, reinvigorating some of the meme-stock excitement that=
 helped make such deals popular early in the year.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The latest special-purpose-acquisition-company excitement focuses o=
n firms like cybersecurity firm IronNet Inc. that suffered significant inve=
stor withdrawals ahead of going public by closing SPAC mergers. High withdr=
awals leave the companies going public with less cash to put into their bus=
inesses and can make it harder for them to meet the growth projections they=
 made as part of the deals with so-called blank-check companies.=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That drop in cash proceeds is why high withdraw=
als have historically sunk share prices. But lately, large withdrawals are =
attracting day traders, making some stocks trend on social-media platforms =
and fueling share-price gains.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Basically you can get the whole meme-stock playbook but in=C2=A0concentrat=
ed form:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A number of factors ar=
e boosting shares after SPAC deals close, investors say. Large investor wit=
hdrawals reduce the number of shares available to trade, also known as a st=
ock=E2=80=99s float. That scarcity means it doesn=E2=80=99t take much to sw=
ing the stock. Companies that go public via SPACs are also popular targets =
for short sellers, who wager on stock-price declines, a trend that can attr=
act day traders hoping to =E2=80=9Csqueeze=E2=80=9D the professionals by bi=
dding up the shares.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Short sellers borrow s=
hares, sell them, then aim to buy them back at lower prices. A low float al=
so makes it challenging for traders to borrow shares. That means it can be =
relatively easy to force those trying to wager on share-price declines to l=
imit losses by buying, analysts say, adding fuel to rallies.=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rising trading in options=E2=80=94which give the ho=
lder the right to buy a stock at a certain price in the future=E2=80=94is a=
lso playing a role. Market makers that sell options often hedge by buying s=
hares of the underlying stock, a force that can help amplify share-price ga=
ins.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you have a SPAC =
with 90% withdrawals that closes its merger anyway, what you are effectivel=
y doing is concentrating the trading of that company entirely in the hands =
of retail meme-stock zealots. Weird stuff happens.</p><table class=3D"livei=
